20:50.549 --> 20:56.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
together. Throughout the year,
our teams will
also report on the big issues
affecting politics

20:56.388 --> 20:58.157 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in America.

20:58.257 --> 21:03.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We bring you our first joint
topic tonight:
the mood and emotions of the
electorate. It's

21:03.496 --> 21:09.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a theme for NPR'S "Morning
Edition," some
local NPR stations this week,
and here at

21:09.935 --> 21:13.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the "NewsHour." We are looking
at the politics
of fear.

21:13.672 --> 21:19.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we just saw, the issue of
fear and terrorism
came up in the forum last night,
and some

21:19.545 --> 21:24.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the candidates have employed
fear of terrorism
as a way to appeal to voters.

21:24.850 --> 21:30.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republican Donald Trump has
called for a ban
on Muslims coming into the U.S.,
saying, "Our

21:30.122 --> 21:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
country cannot be the victim of
tremendous
attacks by people who believe
only in jihad."

21:36.495 --> 21:42.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Senator Ted Cruz has warned,
"Our enemies
are not tired of killing us. And
they're getting

21:42.168 --> 21:48.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stronger," while Senator Marco
Rubio cautioned,
"What happened in Paris could
happen here.

21:48.107 --> 21:51.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
