recruiter. They
are going to people showing
videos of Donald

22:02.488 --> 22:04.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump insulting Islam."

22:04.990 --> 22:09.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For our discussion on this,
we're joined now
by Stephen Walt, professor of
international

22:09.895 --> 22:15.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
affairs at Harvard University,
and Beverly
Gage. She's a professor of 20th
century American

22:15.901 --> 22:18.504 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
history at Yale University.

22:18.604 --> 22:20.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we welcome you both.

22:20.272 --> 22:22.041 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Beverly Gage, to you first.

22:22.141 --> 22:28.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How long have candidates used
fear in one
form or another in American
politics? And

22:28.180 --> 22:30.049 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
how successful has it been?

22:30.149 --> 22:31.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BEVERLY GAGE, Assistant
Professor of American
History, Yale University: Well,
I would like

22:31.984 --> 22:35.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to say it's a brand-new thing,
and we can
just tamp it down, but there's
always been

22:35.387 --> 22:37.656 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a certain element of fear
politics.

22:37.756 --> 22:42.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Really, if you look back to the
founding fathers,
they were accusing each other of
all sorts

22:42.228 --> 22:47.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of things. The Federalists were
accusing their
opponents of all sorts of
conspiracies. So,

22:47.833 --> 22:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think we have a very long
history.

22:50.669 --> 22:56.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think, oftentimes, as we're
seeing today,
that history is tied up in both
foreign affairs

22:56.442 --> 23:00.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then issues at home, issues
like race
and crime and immigration.

23:00.246 --> 23:05.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stephen Walt,
what about the
use of fear as a tactic through
history? How

23:05.784 --> 23:07.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
successful do you think it's
been?

23:07.686 --> 23:09.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN WALT, Harvard University
Kennedy School
of Government: Well, I think
it's been used

23:09.521 --> 23:12.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
successfully by a number of
candidates in
the past and been used by
candidates from

23:13.058 --> 23:14.827 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
both parties.

23:14.927 --> 23:18.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You will recall, in the late
'40s and early
1950s, the Truman administration
was accused

23:18.864 --> 23:24.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of losing China, being soft on
communism.
The claim was made by Joseph
McCarthy that

23:24.436 --> 23:27.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
communists were infiltrating key
American
institutions.

23:28.073 --> 23:32.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, in 1960, John F.
Kennedy turned
the tables and accused the
Eisenhower administration

23:33.045 --> 23:38.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of also being weak, of allowing
a missile
gap to develop, even though none
existed.

23:38.717 --> 23:43.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this tactic of trying to
play on people's
fears and insecurities is a
pretty common

23:43.889 --> 23:45.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one, as Beverly said.

23:45.891 --> 23:50.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Beverly,
used pretty equally
by both political parties, or
has one party

23:50.663 --> 23:52.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or another used it more? What do
you see?

23:53.098 --> 23:57.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: Well, I certainly
think, in
the 20th century, you can go
cherry-picking

23:57.936 --> 24:00.139 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and find both parties using it.

24:00.239 --> 24:08.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, probably the most famous
example of fear
politics in a campaign actually
was a Democrat

24:08.347 --> 24:14.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
defaming a Republican, so,
Lyndon Johnson
and Barry Goldwater, Johnson's
famous ad that

24:14.119 --> 24:19.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
showed a little girl picking off
the petals
of a daisy, accusing Barry
Goldwater being

24:19.792 --> 24:21.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about to foment nuclear war.

24:21.727 --> 24:26.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think you can see it
happening on both
sides. But I think the more
interesting question

24:26.198 --> 24:31.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is sort of, what position are
candidates usually
in when they're using this kind
of politics?

24:31.904 --> 24:36.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while there are exceptions,
it's often
candidates who are in the
opposition party,

24:36.375 --> 24:41.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it's often candidates who
are trying to
appeal to people who feel like
they have something

24:42.014 --> 24:43.816 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to lose.

24:43.916 --> 24:47.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if a candidate comes in and
says, that's
right, the terrible thing that
you fear may

24:47.386 --> 24:52.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
happen is in fact going to
happen, that, unfortunately,
can be a pretty effective
tactic.

24:52.391 --> 24:57.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Stephen Walt,
telescope
that to this year. How do you
see it playing

24:57.930 --> 25:02.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out in this campaign? I just
used some quotes
from some of the candidates a
minute ago,

25:02.267 --> 25:04.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but what do you see?

25:04.169 --> 25:07.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN WALT: Well, what I think
is interesting
about this campaign is the
degree to which

25:07.873 --> 25:13.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's fear of the other, fear of
the alien,
fear of those who aren't really
fully American

25:14.079 --> 25:21.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or aren't potentially -- or
maybe disloyal
in some fashion, so pointing to
Mexican Americans,

25:21.153 --> 25:22.921 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pointing to Muslim Americans.

25:23.021 --> 25:27.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this theme has actually been
throughout
Obama's presidency, when you
think about it,

25:27.893 --> 25:33.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the various bizarre accusations
that he wasn't
really American or he was
secretly Muslim

25:33.532 --> 25:41.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
himself, this notion that
somehow these people
can't be trusted and real
Americans face dangers

25:41.774 --> 25:43.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that may be enormous.

25:43.575 --> 25:48.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, we have seen this in
the past.
This was clearly part of the
McCarthy period.

25:49.014 --> 25:54.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think it's the thing that
is most telling
about 2016. And you even see it
in a slightly

25:54.253 --> 26:00.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
different form with the Sanders
campaign suggesting
that most of the problems in
America are due

26:00.225 --> 26:05.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the greedy 1 percenters of
Wall Street,
and if we could just get them
under control,

26:05.264 --> 26:06.832 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we would be fine.

26:06.932 --> 26:09.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think that is what defines
the use of
fear in this particular
campaign.

26:09.735 --> 26:15.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Beverly
Gage, how do we
distinguish between what's a
responsible,

26:15.574 --> 26:22.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
healthy debate over real threats
to this country,
vs. crossing a line into
something that's

26:22.481 --> 26:24.716 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just playing on people's fears
and insecurities?

26:24.817 --> 26:28.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: Right. Well, that
is the big
question.

26:28.420 --> 26:34.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, often, we are dealing with
real issues.
So, terrorism is a real issue,
and, in fact,

26:34.326 --> 26:39.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
immigration itself is also a
real issue. We
are now at peak levels of
immigration, levels

26:39.465 --> 26:44.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of immigration we haven't seen
really since
the turn of the last century.
So, there is

26:44.269 --> 26:47.339 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something driving this kind of
politics.

26:47.439 --> 26:52.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the question is
exactly what you
have posed. How do you kind of
deal responsibly

26:52.845 --> 26:58.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with it? It would be nice to
say, well, you
just present the facts, but,
often, that actually

26:58.383 --> 27:03.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is not what really works. I
think Obama tried
to do that in terms of terrorism
at his State

27:03.889 --> 27:08.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the Union, when he said, you
know, we're
not in the middle of World War
III. We are

27:08.260 --> 27:10.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not at risk as a nation.

27:10.329 --> 27:15.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I'm not sure that actually
played very
well. I think, often, what can
make the real

27:15.334 --> 27:20.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
difference is actually shifting
the debate
a little bit, acknowledging that
the problem

27:20.405 --> 27:25.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is real, and the question is not
how to freak
out about it, but, in fact, how
to begin to

27:25.844 --> 27:27.646 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
deal with it constructively.

27:27.746 --> 27:32.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stephen Walt,
have you seen
examples of candidates handling
it well this

27:32.417 --> 27:38.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year? And who's responsible for
getting it
all straightened out and making
sure people

27:38.323 --> 27:44.062 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
know what's -- what is
responsible, what's
healthy, and what's crossing a
line?

27:44.162 --> 27:48.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN WALT: Well, certainly,
there's a role
for the candidates to challenge
each other.

27:48.166 --> 27:53.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think one of the things
candidates can
do is first force their rivals
to be specific.

27:53.305 --> 27:58.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Don't just point to some menace
whose dimensions
are being exaggerated, but force
people to

27:58.310 --> 28:03.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be concrete and specific about
the policies
that they would follow, what
they would do

28:03.515 --> 28:07.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
differently, how they would make
the problem
manageable.

28:07.519 --> 28:12.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Don't treat it, again, as this
infinitely
large menace, but rather as a
practical problem

28:12.724 --> 28:17.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be solved. There's also,
obviously, a role
here for the media in
challenging the various

28:18.030 --> 28:23.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
claims from the candidates,
asking them for
specifics, asking them for
facts, and not

28:23.802 --> 28:26.271 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
accepting magical solutions.

28:26.371 --> 28:30.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It shouldn't be acceptable for a
candidate
to be able to say, look, we're
facing a huge

28:30.642 --> 28:36.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
danger here, but I have an easy
way to solve
this particular huge danger.

28:36.281 --> 28:42.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Then, finally, I think
candidates can play
a certain jujitsu on their
rivals by basically

28:42.754 --> 28:47.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
saying, those who are
fear-mongering don't
have enough confidence in
America's basic

28:47.826 --> 28:50.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
strengths, don't have confidence
in America's
institutions.

28:50.963 --> 28:57.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think Ronald Reagan was
the modern genius
at this. He used fear-mongering
in the 1980

28:57.603 --> 29:02.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
campaign against Jimmy Carter,
but he also
managed to do it with a sense of
great optimism,

29:02.808 --> 29:08.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that America was fundamentally
good, fundamentally
strong, and these challenges
were something

29:08.447 --> 29:10.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it could overcome.

29:10.282 --> 29:13.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If any of the candidates can
manage that sweet
spot, they're likely to do
pretty well.

29:14.052 --> 29:19.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Beverly Gage,
that means
that there's promise out there
that candidates

29:19.424 --> 29:21.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will handle it well this year
and beyond?

29:21.827 --> 29:26.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: There is promise
out there.
I think there are also some dark
examples

29:26.765 --> 29:28.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from American history.

29:28.800 --> 29:34.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, another moment in which
terrorism, immigration
was really on the table was in
the teens and

29:34.773 --> 29:39.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the '20s. And what we actually
got coming
out of that political moment
was, in fact,

29:39.945 --> 29:46.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pretty extreme immigration
restriction, as
well as the rise of the new Ku
Klux Klan during

29:46.985 --> 29:48.754 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that period.

29:48.854 --> 29:51.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think there's a lot at
stake, and I
think we're still early in the
campaign, and

29:51.223 --> 29:52.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we will see how it goes.

29:53.091 --> 29:56.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A lot at stake.
And you're
right, we are really early in
the campaign.

29:56.361 --> 29:56.995 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

29:57.095 --> 29:59.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We will see.

29:59.164 --> 30:01.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Beverly Gage, Stephen Walt, we
thank you both.

30:01.500 --> 30:03.101 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: Thank you, Judy.

30:03.201 --> 30:08.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN WALT: Nice talking with
you.

