shame of our nation, when you
look at, a student
comes out of high school, not
knowing what

31:50.075 --> 31:56.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they want to do, goes to
college, drops out.
Now they're in debt, without a
job, and not

31:56.214 --> 32:00.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
knowing what they want to do.
They're worse
off than they were, you know, as
little as

32:00.118 --> 32:04.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a year before. And that's all
preventable,
all of it.

32:04.556 --> 32:10.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: One solution,
principal Dave
Wheeler says, lies in schools
like his, Southeastern

32:10.729 --> 32:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Regional Vocational Technical
High School,
south of Boston.

32:14.633 --> 32:19.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here, in addition to the regular
school subjects,
students learn skilled trades
and professions,

32:20.038 --> 32:24.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, if they choose, instead of
college, they
can go directly into the work
force.

32:24.676 --> 32:29.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WHEELER: You can become
anything you
want here, if you take advantage
of what we

32:29.614 --> 32:31.550 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
have.

32:31.650 --> 32:35.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Choosing a career
program starts
in ninth grade. Students spend
the first semester

32:35.554 --> 32:39.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sampling each of the roughly 20
professions
taught here.

32:39.257 --> 32:42.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dajon Lopes (ph) chose culinary
arts.

32:42.227 --> 32:46.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAJON LOPES, Student: We learn
to cook everything,
a whole bunch of foreign dishes,
American

32:46.164 --> 32:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dishes, anything. You name it,
we got it.

32:48.500 --> 32:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This right here is Asian scallop
saute.

32:50.902 --> 32:53.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Is this a new dish
for you?

32:54.005 --> 32:54.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAJON LOPES: Yes. It's my first
time, matter
of fact.

32:55.040 --> 32:56.908 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: The first time,
yes? May I?

32:57.008 --> 32:57.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAULA KFOURY, Southeastern
Regional Vocational
Technical High School: It's not
like you're

32:57.909 --> 32:59.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opening a book and reading about
it.

32:59.144 --> 33:00.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Culinary arts
teacher Paula
Kfoury.

33:00.779 --> 33:01.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAULA KFOURY: It's hands-on,
which is so different.

33:01.746 --> 33:03.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: That's very nice.

33:03.548 --> 33:09.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAULA KFOURY: They come in here
every day
and open a restaurant. And we do
all of the

33:09.521 --> 33:10.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
functions for the school.

33:10.922 --> 33:13.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: This car has -- gave us a
lot of problems.

33:13.758 --> 33:16.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: In collision
repair, the work
is also real.

33:16.361 --> 33:20.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: A customer brings in a car,
we, like,
do a estimate on it.

33:20.699 --> 33:22.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: This is someone's
car?

33:22.567 --> 33:25.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Yes. And then, after that
we call the
customer up, we tell them how
much it will

33:25.303 --> 33:27.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cost, and we start repairing it.

33:27.138 --> 33:33.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WHEELER: Almost all of our
shops do
some form of, we call it live
work. Cosmetology

33:33.578 --> 33:40.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
takes clients. Construction, we
have done
complete renovations of
buildings. We have

33:40.318 --> 33:45.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
done Web sites for people. We do
printing.
There is no better way to engage
a student

33:45.857 --> 33:47.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
than they're doing real,
meaningful work.

33:48.026 --> 33:53.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Of course, they
also do academics.
Every other week, students are
in traditional

33:53.632 --> 33:55.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
classes full-time.

33:55.700 --> 34:00.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WHEELER: Every single kid
is going to
learn algebra. Everyone's going
to get a high-level

34:00.939 --> 34:03.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
literature class. Everyone's
going to get
physics.

34:03.441 --> 34:09.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: On the state math
test, 73 percent
of students scored above
proficient, in English,

34:09.781 --> 34:15.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
90 percent, numbers that nearly
match state
averages. And Southeastern's 93
percent graduation

34:15.687 --> 34:17.856 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rate is better than average.

34:17.956 --> 34:23.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the flip side, SAT scores and
scores on
advanced placement tests lag
significantly

34:23.328 --> 34:28.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
behind the state as a whole.
But, for Dave
Wheeler, those are not the
numbers that matter

34:28.800 --> 34:30.535 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
most.

34:30.635 --> 34:34.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WHEELER: When we do
follow-up studies,
generally speaking, we hit the
90 -- high

34:34.839 --> 34:39.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
90 percent range of students
that are either
in the work force, continue to
be enrolled

34:39.511 --> 34:44.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in college, or have gone into
the military.
The point is to get you to be a
happy, productive

34:45.083 --> 34:46.885 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
citizen.

34:46.985 --> 34:51.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: This approach is
getting lots
of attention from reformers
these days, who

34:51.556 --> 34:55.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see it as a way to improve
engagement and
achievement in high schools.

34:55.627 --> 35:00.565 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But career and technical
education, or CTE,
as it's sometimes called, has
its critics.

35:00.665 --> 35:05.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAROL BURRIS, Network for Public
Education:
Even though that is what people
are touting

35:05.737 --> 35:13.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a possibility, rigorous CTE
programs, in
the reality, I don't think it's
going to happen.

35:13.111 --> 35:18.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: During her 15
years as an award-winning
high school principal in New
York state, Carol

35:18.183 --> 35:20.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Burris had an insider's view on
these programs.

35:20.585 --> 35:27.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAROL BURRIS: I think a lot of
schools will
take kids that are behavior
issues and will

35:27.459 --> 35:32.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say, you know what, I think
technical education
is where you need to be. I think
they will

35:32.497 --> 35:37.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take kids who have learning
disabilities,
and rather than work with them
in academics,

35:37.235 --> 35:41.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
push them on that track. We just
know that
historically.

35:41.172 --> 35:47.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Almost from the
start, high
schools were organized into
tracks, with separate

35:48.046 --> 35:52.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
programs for students bound for
college and
those bound for work.

35:52.817 --> 35:55.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL PETRILLI, The Thomas B.
Fordham Institute:
And, oftentimes, the way the
system made that

35:55.253 --> 35:59.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decision was based on the color
of their skin
or by their zip code. You can
imagine that

35:59.924 --> 36:04.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it was mostly kids of color and
low-income
kids who were shuffled into
vocational programs,

36:04.829 --> 36:06.498 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
many of which were terrible.

36:06.598 --> 36:10.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: But Mike Petrilli
who heads
the Thomas Fordham Institute, an
education

36:10.135 --> 36:12.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think tank, says a major shift
was coming.

36:12.570 --> 36:17.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE PETRILLI: There was a big
effort to de-track
the high schools and the middle
schools starting

36:17.675 --> 36:20.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the late 1980s, early '90s,
which was very
successful in most big cities.

36:21.079 --> 36:24.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TONY CARNEVALE, Georgetown
University: We
decided that we were going to
give academic

36:24.849 --> 36:30.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
education, which essentially
teaches abstraction,
we decided to give that to
everybody through

36:30.221 --> 36:31.990 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
high school.

36:32.090 --> 36:35.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: The mission of
public schools
changed, says economist Tony
Carnevale, and

36:35.527 --> 36:37.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
college became the goal.

36:37.395 --> 36:41.599 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TONY CARNEVALE: The basic
American model is
high school to Harvard. The
difficulty with

36:41.699 --> 36:45.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is, it doesn't work for
most students.
You ask the teacher, why am I
taking this

36:46.037 --> 36:50.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
course? And they will say, well,
you need
it for college, and that's
enough. For a lot

36:50.275 --> 36:51.776 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of kids, that's not enough.

36:51.876 --> 36:55.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Many arrive at
college unprepared,
fall behind and drop out.

36:55.780 --> 36:59.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE PETRILLI: It would be a lot
better for
those people to go out into the
work force,

36:59.818 --> 37:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get some real skills, and maybe
down the road
they would be ready then to go
and get a postsecondary

37:05.457 --> 37:07.292 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
credential.

37:07.392 --> 37:09.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUSTIN MEEKS, Southeastern
Regional Vocational
Technical High School Graduate:
Schoolwork

37:09.227 --> 37:11.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wasn't -- I wasn't the greatest
at it. I feel
like I'm more of a hands-on
person.

37:11.329 --> 37:15.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: For Justin Meeks,
fabricating
metal was a better fit. He
learned the trade

37:16.067 --> 37:20.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at Southeastern and, through an
apprenticeship
arranged by the school, landed a
full-time

37:20.605 --> 37:22.674 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
job just days after graduation.

37:22.774 --> 37:28.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUSTIN MEEKS, School prepared me
well for
this. I weld here a lot. I have
to cut well

37:28.146 --> 37:29.380 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on here and very accurate.

37:29.481 --> 37:31.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: You can't make a
mistake on
a beam like this.

37:31.850 --> 37:33.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUSTIN MEEKS: Yes, you can't fix
it.

37:33.284 --> 37:36.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: If you don't mind
my asking,
how much do you make?

37:36.521 --> 37:40.558 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUSTIN MEEKS: Fourteen
sixty-six. And if I
can keep getting more money and
more money,

37:40.658 --> 37:44.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a raise, and working harder,
I think I
could be fine without college.

37:44.662 --> 37:46.931 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Is this a success?

37:47.031 --> 37:51.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE PETRILLI: First of all,
let's look at
the alternative. If this was a
young person

37:51.469 --> 37:56.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who wasn't doing well in school,
if he hadn't
been engaged in something that
really motivated

37:56.407 --> 37:59.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
him, he probably would have
dropped out or
maybe he would have made it to
graduation,

37:59.677 --> 38:04.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then that was it. And then
he'd be going
into the work force and lucky to
get a minimum

38:04.716 --> 38:07.218 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wage job. This is a much better
outcome.

38:07.318 --> 38:11.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: And Petrilli says
vocational
schools like Justin's are
different these

38:11.422 --> 38:15.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
days, because, at places like
Southeastern,
tracking is a thing of the past.

38:15.794 --> 38:20.598 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE PETRILLI: It's very
important that the
pathways are chosen by the kids
themselves.

38:20.698 --> 38:23.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to provide options, and
let the young
people make decisions.

38:23.201 --> 38:28.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAROL BURRIS: I think it's very
dangerous.
I have seen so many kids who
have been academic

38:28.973 --> 38:34.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
late bloomers, who all of sudden
they mature
and they buckle down and they do
their studies

38:34.245 --> 38:35.914 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and they go on to college.

38:36.014 --> 38:42.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you start to push kids when
they are
too young to make that decision,
they're just

38:43.087 --> 38:44.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not ready to make it.

38:45.023 --> 38:49.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: But that's not
stopping families
from enrolling their teenagers
at Southeastern.

38:49.561 --> 38:53.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This year, some 800 students
applied for 400
spots.

38:53.665 --> 39:01.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In South Easton, Massachusetts,
I'm John Tulenko
of Education Week, reporting for
the "PBS

39:01.940 --> 39:04.709 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
NewsHour."

39:04.809 --> 39:17.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A federal health
panel is now
calling for all women to be
screened for depression

39:17.689 --> 39:21.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
during pregnancy and again after
giving birth.

39:21.125 --> 39:26.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. Preventive Services
Task Force says
there's new evidence that
postpartum depression

39:26.531 --> 39:32.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is more common than previously
believed. The
report also recommends that all
adults over

39:32.136 --> 39:34.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
18 be screened for depression.

39:35.006 --> 39:38.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham zeros in on the
new guidelines
and how they apply to women

39:38.876 --> 39:42.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Today's
recommendations
follow recent research
suggesting that as

39:42.914 --> 39:48.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many as one in five women may
develop depression,
anxiety or other forms of mental
illness within

39:48.486 --> 39:50.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a year of giving birth.

39:50.421 --> 39:55.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me to discuss this is
Dr. Hal Lawrence.
He's a longtime OB/GYN and
currently the CEO

39:55.660 --> 39:58.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the American Congress of
Obstetricians
and Gynecologists.

39:58.730 --> 40:00.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dr. Lawrence, welcome. Thank you
for being
here.

40:01.099 --> 40:01.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE, CEO, American
Congress of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists:
Thank you

40:01.666 --> 40:03.501 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for inviting us.

40:03.601 --> 40:05.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: What was your
reaction when
you first heard these
guidelines? Was this

40:05.637 --> 40:06.571 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
good news to you?

40:06.671 --> 40:08.406 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: It's excellent
news to us.

40:08.506 --> 40:11.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the American Congress of
Obstetricians
and Gynecologists, we have been
aware for

40:12.043 --> 40:17.682 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
decades about the risk of
postpartum depression,
and, in all honesty, the risk of
depression

40:17.782 --> 40:19.917 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in women at any -- throughout
their life.

40:20.018 --> 40:23.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, one in five women, or
20 percent
of all women, will have a major
depressive

40:24.022 --> 40:29.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
episode during their lifetime,
and pregnancy
and other stressful events
increase that for

40:29.727 --> 40:31.496 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

40:31.596 --> 40:33.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Why is it --
I'm curious.
Just why is it that pregnancy is
a particular

40:33.965 --> 40:35.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
trigger for that?

40:35.800 --> 40:37.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Well, it's
such a stressful
time. And everybody looks at
pregnancy as

40:37.902 --> 40:39.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this joyous moment.

40:39.837 --> 40:45.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is joyous, and you have a
healthy mother,
and you have a healthy baby. But
there's also

40:45.109 --> 40:52.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of stress. That woman's
life has changed.
She feels -- she's so dedicated
to her baby.

40:52.350 --> 40:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then anything that makes her
feel uncomfortable,
she questions herself: Am I
doing the right

40:58.056 --> 40:59.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
thing? Am I doing it good
enough?

41:00.091 --> 41:04.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for some women, that just
sort of works
through with the postpartum
blues, which almost

41:04.696 --> 41:11.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
every postpartum patient has.
But, by a week
or two or three weeks, that
really passes.

41:11.302 --> 41:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for about 20 percent, it
doesn't. It hangs
on for a while, and they
actually have some

41:16.174 --> 41:21.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
depression. And then, for a much
smaller group,
around 2 percent, they can
actually go into

41:21.646 --> 41:26.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something called postpartum
psychosis, which
they can have ideations of
suicide, hurting

41:26.384 --> 41:28.086 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
themselves, hurting their baby.

41:28.186 --> 41:33.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's all because of the
stress of that
period, and at times feelings of
not being

41:33.891 --> 41:37.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what they want to be or being
what people
expect them to be.

41:37.528 --> 41:42.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: These
recommendations indicate
that mothers should be screened
not just after

41:42.233 --> 41:47.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the birth, but during their
pregnancy. And
I wonder why -- is it that signs
during pregnancy

41:47.572 --> 41:49.340 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tend to show up?

41:49.440 --> 41:51.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Well, as I
said, we know
that 20 percent of all women
will have some

41:51.876 --> 41:56.848 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
depression during their
lifetime, and so some
women actually enter pregnancy
with some signs

41:56.948 --> 41:58.883 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of depression.

41:58.983 --> 42:04.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some may have already had a
diagnosis of depression
or psychological illness, and
those people

42:04.622 --> 42:10.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are at increased risk. So,
picking that up
early, or if you don't know
about it, helps

42:10.294 --> 42:14.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you be careful about those
parents when they
become postpartum.

42:14.632 --> 42:20.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, screening during pregnancy
is very important.
Screening postpartum is very
important, and

42:20.938 --> 42:25.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
screening, you know, earlier
than even six
weeks. You know, it's
interesting. Many times,

42:25.843 --> 42:31.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the pediatricians who are seeing
the babies
back for growth checks and
weight gain and

42:31.416 --> 42:34.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all that will pick up on this,
because there
will be...

42:34.485 --> 42:36.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Pick up on the
mother's
behavior.

42:36.421 --> 42:42.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Exactly,
because there's
this detachment between the mom
and the baby,

42:42.660 --> 42:44.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
which is not normal.

42:44.495 --> 42:48.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they -- oftentimes, the
pediatricians
will call and say, hey, there's
something

42:48.366 --> 42:52.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going on here. You need to see
Mrs. Jones,
because it's -- they sense that.

42:53.004 --> 42:57.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: If you were a
doctor sitting
opposite me, what does a
screening for depression

42:57.375 --> 42:59.210 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
look like or sound like?

42:59.310 --> 43:01.846 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Well,
actually, there are
some tools that are out there.
They have this

43:01.946 --> 43:08.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Edinburgh postpartum depression
screen, which
has a series of questions that
are very simple

43:08.586 --> 43:12.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and straightforward. It takes
just a few minutes
for the patients to fill out.

43:12.590 --> 43:16.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can quickly grade it, and
based on how
you grade it, gives you an idea
as to how

43:16.994 --> 43:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this woman's emotional stability
is at that
time. So, we recommend that or a
tool like

43:22.366 --> 43:24.202 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that for everybody to utilize.

43:24.302 --> 43:28.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The reason I
ask about this
is that whenever we have a --
for instance,

43:28.573 --> 43:32.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a major episode of gun violence,
people always
talk about the need to increase
mental health

43:32.944 --> 43:34.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
care in this country.

43:34.846 --> 43:38.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the retorts to that
is always,
we don't have the mental health
infrastructure

43:38.749 --> 43:42.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to handle all those people. I'm
just wondering,
do you think that there's a
concern that these

43:42.220 --> 43:46.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
guidelines might be recommending
services
that we don't have the ability
to deliver?

43:47.058 --> 43:51.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Well, I think
we have to
have the ability to deliver
those services.

43:52.096 --> 43:57.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, yes, there is a good reason
to expand
mental health services in this
country. But

43:57.668 --> 44:01.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when you look at the postpartum
patient, I
think it's really a team. Yes,
oftentimes,

44:01.973 --> 44:08.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you need a psychologist or a
psychiatrist,
but, many times, you need an
alert pediatrician,

44:08.212 --> 44:14.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
an alert and sensitive
obstetrician/gynecologist,
family members who see this is
going on, and

44:14.819 --> 44:20.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that team working to help
support and ensure
that the mother's getting the
support and

44:20.491 --> 44:22.460 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
care she needs.

44:22.560 --> 44:26.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have to -- when we recognize
it -- I mean,
I have practiced for almost 30
years and delivered

44:26.564 --> 44:32.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over 5,000 babies. I have made
this diagnosis.
I have started these people on
treatment.

44:32.436 --> 44:35.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have to do that and see if
you can't get
them healthy.

44:35.640 --> 44:41.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Dr. Hal
Lawrence of the
American Congress of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists,

44:41.212 --> 44:42.446 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
thank you very much.

44:42.547 --> 44:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. HAL LAWRENCE: Thank you.
It's a pleasure
to be here.

44:47.518 --> 45:00.197 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: genius in
three notes.

45:00.298 --> 45:03.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tomorrow marks Wolfgang Amadeus
Mozart's birthday.

45:03.634 --> 45:09.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We celebrate with a conversation
Jeffrey Brown
had recently with composer and
pianist Rob

45:09.540 --> 45:13.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kapilow, who deconstructs music
for us from
time to time.

45:13.544 --> 45:17.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They met up at the Signature
Theatre in Arlington,
Virginia.

45:17.448 --> 45:20.818 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Happy birthday,
Mozart, right?

45:20.918 --> 45:23.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW, Composer: Yes.

45:23.254 --> 45:26.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Welcome, Rob
Kapilow.

45:26.157 --> 45:29.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's start by acknowledging
this is one of
the world's great musical
geniuses, right?

45:29.727 --> 45:33.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: So true. I mean,
just, whenever
you think of musical prodigy,
who do you think

45:33.631 --> 45:38.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of but Mozart? Writing simple
keyboard pieces
at 5, violin sonatas and
orchestral music

45:38.836 --> 45:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at 6 and 7, first symphony at 9.
It's really
disgusting, if you're a composer
like me.

45:43.641 --> 45:45.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You just don't even want to
think about Mozart's
birthday.

45:45.176 --> 45:46.978 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:47.078 --> 45:49.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so
there's a whole
world of Mozart to choose from.
You picked

45:49.513 --> 45:54.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Symphony Number 40, right, the
famous G minor,
and the beginning of that. So,
first, remind

45:54.652 --> 45:56.053 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
us a little of how that...

45:56.153 --> 45:58.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Right. Yes. This is
on everybody's
cell phone ring tone.

45:58.189 --> 46:00.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:00.124 --> 46:01.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Everyone has heard
this, even
if you think you have never
heard a note of...

46:01.459 --> 46:01.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

46:01.926 --> 46:03.160 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

46:03.260 --> 46:03.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: ... music, this is
the one you
have heard.

46:03.661 --> 46:14.872 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
For

46:14.972 --> 46:18.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many generations of kids, this
was actually
ruined as, it's a bird, it's a
plane, no,

46:18.876 --> 46:22.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's Mozart. And now I have
ruined it for
generations of television
viewers as well.

46:22.413 --> 46:24.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. Yes. So, why
pick that?
Why? Why?

46:24.315 --> 46:27.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: I picked this
because, for one,
it's the most famous or one of
the most famous

46:28.052 --> 46:29.887 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
themes that Mozart ever wrote.

46:29.987 --> 46:34.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But what happens to it is
amazing. I often
say that classical music is
really about becoming,

46:34.725 --> 46:35.159 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not being.

46:35.259 --> 46:36.060 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

46:36.160 --> 46:37.895 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Becoming, not
being.

46:37.995 --> 46:41.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes. It's not what
a musical
idea is when you first hear it,
what it is

46:41.766 --> 46:46.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be, but it's about what it
can become or
how it transforms over the
course of a piece

46:46.370 --> 46:48.205 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of music.

46:48.305 --> 46:51.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, in and of itself, while
that's a famous
theme, it's not that amazing, in
and of itself.

46:51.308 --> 46:59.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has got a three-note idea.
That's not so
great. He does it once, does it
again, a third

46:59.684 --> 47:01.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
time, and then leaps up.

47:01.552 --> 47:03.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm now going to ruin this
again for a
new generation. I'm going to
call it, do it

47:03.421 --> 47:09.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
once, do it twice, and then leap
up. In and
of itself, that's not so
fantastic by itself.

47:09.560 --> 47:14.532 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The second half sounds
completely different.
It just goes down a scale.
Though the two

47:14.632 --> 47:17.468 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
halves are actually connected,
they rhyme,
they have the same rhythm.

47:17.568 --> 47:19.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

47:19.503 --> 47:22.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Now, in and of
itself, if Mozart
had stopped there, we wouldn't
be celebrating

47:22.373 --> 47:25.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his birthday hundreds of years
later. It's
not that great.

47:25.309 --> 47:30.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what happens to it over the
course of
the piece is amazing. Let's skip
ahead to

47:30.781 --> 47:43.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the middle of the piece. All of
a sudden,
we end up here. This is a normal
place to

47:43.227 --> 47:52.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
end. All of a sudden, three
abrupt chords
take to us a completely
different place. Where

47:52.770 --> 47:55.506 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are we? We hear our opening.

47:55.606 --> 48:01.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, originally, it was here. We
are now starting
on a different note, what we
call transposing,

48:01.645 --> 48:05.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and we do it here. All sounds
normal.

48:05.483 --> 48:06.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

48:06.884 --> 48:22.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Everyone expects to
hear this,
but, instead, we get

48:22.299 --> 48:23.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
first shock.

48:23.667 --> 48:25.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's through
the key change
first, yes? Yes.

48:25.536 --> 48:27.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Absolutely, first
three key changes,
and then change the melody. Then
we do it

48:27.671 --> 48:30.074 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
again.

48:30.174 --> 48:40.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everyone expects -- but, no, we
get second
shock. Then we hear it again,
third time,

48:40.785 --> 48:46.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even lower. And then the piece
just takes
off.

48:46.624 --> 48:50.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this is like a character in
a novel who
you think you have met. You
think you understand

48:50.961 --> 48:55.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them. But now, all of a sudden,
what he's
going to do is almost
Beethovenian. Now, Beethoven

48:55.399 --> 48:59.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was actually only 18 years old
and still a
babe in the woods, but this is
fundamentally

48:59.436 --> 49:01.205 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Beethovenian.

49:01.305 --> 49:08.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's he's going to do is take
an eight-measure
melody, reduce it to four
measures, reduce

49:08.946 --> 49:12.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it to two measures, 10 notes,
seven notes,
and finally the whole universe
will get summed

49:12.883 --> 49:15.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up in only three notes. So,
watch this.

49:15.519 --> 49:16.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: The whole
universe.

49:16.987 --> 49:18.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: The whole universe
in three notes,
a cosmic essence.

49:19.056 --> 49:20.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

49:20.991 --> 49:24.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: We hear Mozart
think out loud.
What I can do? And he says what
if I just...

49:24.428 --> 49:25.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

49:25.529 --> 49:26.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Even those three
notes, what...

49:26.831 --> 49:28.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes, what can I do
with these
three notes?

49:28.699 --> 49:33.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's not much. Right? This
is not great.
He says, what if I just take the
ending and

49:33.737 --> 49:45.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
put it down here in the flute
and oboe, and
overlap like this? Try it up
higher, even

49:45.249 --> 49:47.918 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
higher.

49:48.018 --> 50:04.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trying to find out, what does
the idea mean?
And then the ultimate final step
is, we reduce

50:04.568 --> 50:08.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the whole thing to nothing but
the first three
notes. Who would dream that this
could be

50:08.906 --> 50:13.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the topic for an entire piece?

50:13.310 --> 50:22.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We started,
though, this conversation
about genius. Your case is that
that is sort

50:22.820 --> 50:27.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the essence of it, is taking
something
simple, creating a whole
universe in a sense.

50:27.658 --> 50:29.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Exactly.

50:29.460 --> 50:31.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's that quote from Ezra
Pound, genius
is the capacity to see 10 things
where the

50:31.929 --> 50:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ordinary man sees one. We just
hear that opening
idea, but he sees, as you have
just heard,

50:36.600 --> 50:40.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at least 20 things in an idea
that we never
could have imagined.

50:40.304 --> 50:44.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A great Mark Twain quote: "There
never was
yet an uninteresting life."

50:44.241 --> 50:49.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Inside the dullest exterior,
there is a drama,
a comedy and a tragedy. And
Mozart heard the

50:49.813 --> 50:53.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drama, comedy, and tragedy in
all of us, and
turned it into music.

50:53.517 --> 50:55.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, happy
birthday,
Mozart.

50:55.753 --> 50:56.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Rob Kapilow, thanks so much.

50:56.820 --> 51:01.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Thank you.

51:01.592 --> 51:11.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Great music.

